<section class="sec reveal" id="qb-cleanup-after-prior-definition" style="padding-top:24px;">
  <div class="ct read read--doc">
    <div class="eyebrow" style="margin-bottom:8px;">In plain terms</div>
    <h2 class="h2" style="margin-bottom:18px;">Inheriting a prior bookkeeper&rsquo;s file, plainly.</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>When a bookkeeper moves on &mdash; they quit, you let them go, or the work simply wasn&rsquo;t up to standard &mdash; the QuickBooks file doesn&rsquo;t leave with them. You inherit it as it stands, and what&rsquo;s in it is often very different from what the reports suggest. Reconciliations may show as done when they were force-balanced; income and expenses may be categorized inconsistently; undeposited funds and opening-balance-equity may be quietly off; and there&rsquo;s rarely any documentation explaining how the file was kept.</p>
      <p>The good news is that an inherited file is almost always recoverable. We take it over the same way every time: a free review to see what&rsquo;s actually there, a written fixed-fee scope, then reconcile, correct, rebuild the chart of accounts where it&rsquo;s broken, and document the result so the next person never has to reverse-engineer it. We diagnose the file, not the previous bookkeeper. And we&rsquo;re clear about the boundary &mdash; we do the cleanup and produce a CPA-ready file; your CPA or tax preparer files the returns. An Intuit account, login, or billing matter stays with Intuit.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

